        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The project is limited by the cotinuum sensitivity. We configure the correlator for the maximum  bandwith. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our model predicts the inner belt peaked at 13 AU from the star (1.68" in radius at the distance of 7.7 pc). Therefore, a resolution of 0.4" is adequate to resolve the inner broundary of the belt. Furthermore, our cycle-1 data were obtained in a similar configuration, and this is proven to be adequate with the marginal detection (2-sigma) from the cycle-1 data. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We use the SED models, constrained by our cycle-1 data, to predict the expected surface brightness of the inner belt by assuming it has a similar geometry as the large, outer cold belt. The peak flux in the proposed observation is from the star, which is about 1.7 mJy measured from our cycle-1 data. Our favorite model (NR2 in the proposal text) predicts a maximum brightness of 55 uJy/beam at band 7, which is marginally detected in the cycle-1 data. With the C36-3 configuration and continuum setup (7.5 GHz bandwidth), a tota of 6.4 hours on-source integration gives a rms of 9.8 uJy/beam with a synthesized beam of 0.46"x0.41". Therefore, the Fomalhaut's inner belt is expected to be detected at ~5.5 sigma levels. 

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
